e":"1532–Zesnulá","1530–Male":"1530–Zesnulý","1579–1609":"1579–1609","–Male":"Zesnulý","–Female":"Zesnulá","1579":"1579","1532":"1532","1530":"1530","1609":"1609","Kilburn, Yorkshire, England":"Kilburn, Yorkshire, Anglie","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1532–":"1532–Afdød","1532–Female":"1532–Afdød","1530–Male":"1530–Afdød","1579–1609":"1579–1609","–Male":"Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1579":"1579","1532":"1532","1530":"1530","1609":"1609","Kilburn, Yorkshire, England":"Kilburn, Jórvík, England","England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1532–":"1532–Overleden","1532–Female":"1532–Overleden","1530–Male":"1530–Overleden","1579–1609":"1579–1609","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1579":"1579","1532":"1532","1530":"1530","1609":"1609","Kilburn, Yorkshire, England":"Kilburn, Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1532–":"1532–Deceased","1532–Female":"1532–Deceased","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","1579–1609":"1579–1609","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1579":"1579","1532":"1532","1530":"1530","1609":"1609","Kilburn, Yorkshire, England":"Kilburn, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chambers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>chaumbre</i> ‘room (in a house); reception room in a palace or official building’ (Old French <i>chambre</i>). It is identical in implied function with the   Chamberlain  , which denoted an official: to pay <i>in cameram</i> was to pay into the exchequer, of which the <i>camerarius</i> or chamberer was in charge. The surname also applied to clerks employed there. As the office of <i>Chamberlain</i> rose in the social scale, this term remained reserved for more humble servants of the bedchamber or private quarters.","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Les Chambres, Manche (France)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cambareri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Antonio, Carmelo, Giuseppe, Antonino, Fortunato, Francesca, Francesco, Giovanni, Salvatore, Carmela, Cosmo, Rosario.","Italian: variant of <b>Cammareri</b>, an occupational name fromSicilian <i>cammareri</i> ‘servant’. Compare   Chambers  ."]},{"name":"Chalmers","meanings":["Scottish: from Older Scots <i>chalmer</i> ‘chamberlain’; compare   Chambers  . The <i>mb</i> was assimilated to <i>mm</i>; the <i>l</i> was purely graphic, indicating that the preceding <i>a</i> was long.","English: possibly a localized form of <b>Challinor</b> (see   Challender  ), with dissimilation of <i>ln</i> to <i>lm</i> in <i>Chalner</i>."]},{"name":"Chamberlain","meanings":["English: status name from Old French <i>chambrelain</i>, Norman French <i>cambrelanc</i>, <i>cambrelen(c)</i> ‘chamberlain’ (of ancient Germanic origin, from <i>kamer</i> ‘chamber, room’, Latin <i>camera</i> (see   Chambers  ) + the diminutive suffix <i>-(l)ing</i>). This was originally the name of an official in charge of the private chambers of his master, but is so widespread in late medieval England that it must sometimes have been used of people of more ordinary status, perhaps as a nickname for an officious or self-important person or for someone who played the role of chamberlain in a folk play, tableau, or ceremony. Compare   Chancellor   for a possible similar usage."]},{"name":"Chamber","meanings":["English: variant of   Chambers  ."]},{"name":"Chambless","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Chambers  .Compare   Chambliss  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mary Chambers was born in 1532, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sir John Halse Chambers and Lady Johane Chambers. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Richard Kirby."},"et":{"1532–":"1532–Surn